\section{Introduction}
% -------------------------------------------------------

Traditional educational assessments adopt a one-size-fits-all model, presenting identical questions to all students regardless of individual competency. This approach inherently assumes uniform learning ability and pace among learners, which is rarely the case in real-world educational environments. As a result, high-performing students may find the assessment too easy and unchallenging, while low-performing students may struggle excessively, leading to frustration and disengagement. Consequently, such systems fail to capture the true ability of learners at either extreme of the performance spectrum and provide little actionable insight for instructors regarding individual strengths, weaknesses, and learning trajectories \cite{weiss2004}.

Furthermore, most existing assessment systems provide limited or generic feedback that does not help students understand their specific areas of strength and weakness. This lack of personalization hinders accurate competency measurement, reduces student engagement, and limits learning efficiency \cite{vygotsky1978}. Without continuous adaptation based on student performance, assessments remain rigid and unable to reflect the dynamic nature of learning \cite{mislevy2003}. There is therefore a pressing need for an adaptive assessment system that adjusts to each student's abilities in real-time and provides data-driven, contextually intelligent feedback to enhance the learning process.

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) has emerged as a promising paradigm to address these limitations by dynamically adjusting question difficulty based on ongoing student responses \cite{lord1980}. However, most CAT systems rely on Item Response Theory (IRT) models, which require large-scale pre-calibrated item banks and statistically validated parameters for each question \cite{lord1980}. This dependency significantly limits their applicability in smaller educational settings where such datasets are unavailable. Additionally, IRT-based systems often lack transparency, making it difficult for educators to interpret how and why certain questions are selected, thereby reducing trust in formative educational contexts \cite{hambleton1985}.

To address these challenges without imposing rigid mathematical formulas, recent advances in Large Language Models (LLMs) offer an alternative pathway: encoding adaptation logic directly into the reasoning capabilities of intelligent agents. Rather than computing a numerical Learning Index or calibrating difficulty via statistical thresholds, LLM-powered agents can reason over correctness and response time holistically, applying natural language adaptation rules to produce context-aware difficulty decisions.

Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} proposed a recursive APOT model managed by a Multi-Agent System (MAS) for competency building, introducing specialized agents including the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), the Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), the Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and the Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA) for tracking learner progress through competency stages. While their work provides a strong foundation for competency-based learning, their framework primarily focuses on augmented reality (AR)-based vocational training environments involving guided instruction, and relies on quantitative KPI metrics and deterministic indices. Our system adapts the spirit of the APOT model---its cyclic Assess, Predict, Oversee, Transit stages and the role separation embodied by SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA---into a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing environment.

This paper proposes an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System with the following key contributions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A three-agent CrewAI pipeline powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash that maps to the APOT agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA), replacing formula-driven scoring with LLM-native contextual reasoning.
    \item An MCQ Evaluator Agent (implementing the SOLMA role) that assesses answer correctness and provides a natural language explanation.
    \item A Difficulty Predictor Agent (implementing the SOLPA role) that infers question difficulty from correctness and response time using psychometric reasoning encoded in agent prompts.
    \item An Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (implementing the SOLTA role) that synthesizes prior agent outputs to produce both a current difficulty classification and a recommended next-question difficulty, guided by explicit adaptive rules.
    \item A dual-layer difficulty adaptation architecture combining a synchronous rule-based fallback with an asynchronous multi-agent LLM pipeline, and an LLM-driven dynamic question generation mechanism that eliminates dependence on static question banks.
    \item An interpretable, prompt-engineered adaptation mechanism that eliminates IRT pre-calibration while maintaining responsiveness and explainability across three cognitive domains.
\end{enumerate}

