\section{Related Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}
Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) have gained significant attention in educational technology due to their ability to model complex, distributed, and intelligent behaviors \cite{wooldridge2009}. Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT model, which leverages a MAS architecture to manage different stages of competency development. Their system introduces four specialized agents: the \textbf{Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA)}, which evaluates the learner's preferred learning modality; the \textbf{Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA)}, which continuously monitors current performance and progress; the \textbf{Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA)}, which predicts the learner's potential and forecasts difficulty; and the \textbf{Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA)}, which determines when and how to transition the learner to the next competency stage. These agents collaboratively compute a Learning Index (LI) and Competency Index (CI) to monitor learner progress across sessions. However, their framework targets vocational training in AR environments, limiting its direct applicability to digital, question-based assessment contexts \cite{outay2024}. Our work adapts the APOT's multi-agent collaboration philosophy to a question-driven setting, replacing quantitative KPIs with LLM-based reasoning over correctness, time, and difficulty trajectory.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing}
Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) has been extensively studied since the 1970s and is widely regarded as a robust method for personalized assessment \cite{weiss2004}. CAT systems typically rely on IRT, where each question is associated with parameters such as difficulty, discrimination, and guessing probability \cite{lord1980}. While statistically rigorous, IRT-based CAT systems require large, well-calibrated item banks that are expensive and time-consuming to develop \cite{hambleton1985}. The probabilistic nature of IRT models also makes them difficult to interpret for educators. Our approach replaces IRT with LLM-based agents that reason over observable performance signals---correctness and time---using transparent natural language rules, offering ease of deployment without sacrificing adaptive responsiveness.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}
Recent advances in Large Language Models have enabled their integration into educational systems for tasks such as feedback generation, tutoring, and content creation \cite{chen2023}. Frameworks such as CrewAI \cite{liang2023} and AutoGen facilitate the deployment of LLM-augmented multi-agent systems where agents collaborate to perform complex reasoning tasks. Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956} provides a cognitive hierarchy that informs how question difficulty scales with learner ability; our three-level difficulty scheme (Easy, Medium, Hard) is grounded in this framework. Reinforcement learning approaches \cite{sutton2018} and Bayesian student models \cite{conati2002} offer alternatives but require extensive training data or careful prior specification. Unlike prior hybrid systems that restrict LLMs to feedback generation only, our system delegates the full assessment pipeline---including answer evaluation, difficulty prediction, and adaptation decision---to LLM agents, demonstrating that prompt-engineered agents can reliably implement psychometric adaptation logic without deterministic formulas.

