\section{System Architecture}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Assessment Workflow}
The adaptive MCQ difficulty prediction system follows a per-question adaptive loop. For each question presented to the student, the system captures the student's selected answer and the time taken to respond. These inputs are passed to the CrewAI pipeline, which executes three agents sequentially. The MCQ Evaluator Agent (SOLMA) first determines whether the answer is correct or incorrect. The Difficulty Predictor Agent (SOLPA) then classifies the difficulty of the current question based on correctness and time. The Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (SOLTA) synthesizes these results to output both the current question's difficulty classification and the recommended difficulty level for the next question. This loop repeats for each of the 20 questions in the session, enabling real-time adaptation of assessment difficulty across three cognitive domains: Reasoning, Aptitude (with aliases: Quantitative Aptitude, Quant), and Verbal Ability (with aliases: Verbal, English).

\subsection{Architecture Overview}

The system is implemented as a full-stack web application using Django 4.2 (Python) with MySQL as the database backend, and is organized into five interconnected layers with clearly defined responsibilities.

The \textbf{Presentation Layer} consists of Django HTML templates styled with Bootstrap 5.3 and vanilla JavaScript, handling question display, four-option answer input, and a 20-minute countdown timer. A fullscreen enforcement gate using the browser Fullscreen API blocks the test UI until the student opts in, and \texttt{navigator.sendBeacon} provides graceful auto-submission on tab closure. The \textbf{Controller/Orchestration Layer} (Django views) coordinates the test lifecycle---session initialization, answer processing with synchronous rule-based difficulty fallback, skip-question management, and result compilation---and spawns the asynchronous agent pipeline. The \textbf{AI/Agent Pipeline Layer} executes the CrewAI multi-agent pipeline (SOLMA$\rightarrow$SOLPA$\rightarrow$SOLTA) in a background daemon thread, communicating with Gemini 2.5 Flash and persisting results upon completion. The \textbf{Question Generation Layer} invokes Google Gemini via the \texttt{google-generativeai} SDK to generate MCQs on-the-fly at the specified difficulty level, enforcing a strict JSON schema with fields for question text, four options, correct answer, and explanation. The \textbf{Data/Persistence Layer} comprises three MySQL-backed Django models---\texttt{StudentTestResult}, \texttt{QuestionPerformance}, and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory}---providing durable storage for test sessions, per-question AI analysis, and difficulty progression tracking.

\subsection{APOT Model Adaptation}

The original APOT learning model \cite{outay2024} follows a cyclic process of Assess, Predict, Oversee, and Transit stages. In our adaptation, the \textit{Assess} stage maps to the MCQ Evaluator Agent, which implements the \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent) function by determining answer correctness and monitoring the student's immediate performance. The \textit{Predict} stage maps to the Difficulty Predictor Agent, which implements the \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent) function by classifying the current question's difficulty. The \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} stages jointly map to the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent, which implements the \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent) function by reviewing the combined analysis and recommending the next question's difficulty level. The \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is embodied by the domain-aware question generation across three cognitive domains and the multi-domain competency tracking on the analytics dashboard.

\subsection{Dual-Layer Difficulty Adaptation}

A key architectural innovation is the dual-layer difficulty adaptation mechanism that decouples UI responsiveness from the heavier multi-agent LLM pipeline.

\textbf{Synchronous Layer (Rule-Based Fallback).} When the student submits an answer, the controller immediately applies a deterministic rule-based mapping to compute the next difficulty. If the answer is correct: Easy$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Hard, Hard$\rightarrow$Hard. If incorrect: Hard$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Easy, Easy$\rightarrow$Easy. The next question is immediately generated at this difficulty via \texttt{call\_gemini\_api(topic, next\_difficulty, question\_number, total\_questions)} and returned in the JSON response, ensuring sub-second UI updates.

\textbf{Asynchronous Layer (Multi-Agent AI Pipeline).} In parallel, a daemon thread executes the full SOLMA$\rightarrow$SOLPA$\rightarrow$SOLTA CrewAI pipeline via \texttt{analyze\_answer\_with\_crew()}. When complete, the richer AI-derived analysis---including predicted difficulty, reasoning, and recommendations---is persisted to \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} records, and \texttt{StudentTestResult.final\_difficulty} is updated. The thread explicitly closes its thread-local Django database connection in a \texttt{finally} block to prevent connection leaks.

\subsection{Dynamic LLM-Driven Question Generation}

Rather than drawing from a static question bank, the system generates each question on-the-fly by prompting Google Gemini 2.5 Flash with the target topic, difficulty level, and question number. The prompt enforces a strict JSON schema requiring an \texttt{id}, \texttt{question} text, four \texttt{options}, a \texttt{correct\_answer} matching one option exactly, and an \texttt{explanation}. Topics are constrained via a normalized vocabulary with alias mapping (e.g., ``quant'' and ``quantitative aptitude'' resolve to \textit{aptitude}; ``verbal'' and ``verbal ability'' resolve to \textit{english}). Retry logic with exponential-like backoff of $(attempt+1) \times 2$ seconds handles transient API errors (HTTP 503, 429, 500) up to 3 retries, and a stub fallback question is returned if all retries fail. This eliminates the traditional bottleneck of pre-curated item bank construction required by IRT-based systems \cite{lord1980}.

