The trace demonstrates that the system correctly escalates difficulty for students who answer quickly and correctly, reflecting mastery of easy material. Students who answer slowly but correctly are placed at Medium difficulty, reflecting effortful but successful performance. Students who answer incorrectly---regardless of speed---are classified as facing Hard questions and are stepped down, consistent with the adaptive rule set.

\subsection{Competency Analytics and Longitudinal Tracking}

Beyond per-question adaptation, the system provides longitudinal competency tracking. The dashboard computes a Competency Index (CI) as a weighted average over the ten most recent completed tests, with harmonic weights (weight = 1/(rank)) ensuring recent performance has greater influence. Per-domain accuracy (Aptitude, Reasoning, Verbal) is tracked independently, and the weakest domain is identified for targeted feedback. Competency bands are assigned on the leaderboard: Expert ($\geq$85), Advanced ($\geq$70), Intermediate ($\geq$50), and Beginner ($<$50). The three persistence models---\texttt{StudentTestResult} (session-level scores, status, timestamps), \texttt{QuestionPerformance} (per-question AI analysis with \texttt{predicted\_difficulty}, \texttt{crew\_reasoning}, \texttt{crew\_recommendation}), and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} (SOLTA difficulty progressions per question)---form a complete audit trail from individual responses to aggregate competency profiles.

\subsection{Advantages of LLM-Native Adaptation over Formula-Based Approaches}

A key design decision in this system is the delegation of all difficulty reasoning to LLM agents rather than deterministic formulas. This choice offers several advantages. First, the adaptation rules can be expressed and modified entirely in natural language without rewriting scoring code, improving maintainability. Second, the agents can incorporate contextual nuance---such as recognizing borderline cases in time thresholds---that rigid numeric formulas cannot express. Third, the full reasoning chain is available in the agent output, providing educators with a natural language explanation for every difficulty decision, directly supporting the explainability goals outlined in the APOT framework \cite{outay2024}. Fourth, eliminating pre-calibrated IRT parameters makes the system deployable in any domain without prior item bank construction \cite{hambleton1985}. Fifth, the LLM-driven question generation further eliminates the traditional bottleneck: new domains require only a topic name and difficulty level to operate, with no pilot testing or statistical calibration.

The primary trade-off is the non-determinism inherent in LLM outputs, which means identical inputs may occasionally produce slightly different outputs. This is mitigated by the structured output format enforced through task descriptions, the line-by-line keyword parsing with hard ``Medium'' defaults on failure, and critically by the synchronous rule-based fallback layer that guarantees deterministic behavior for the real-time question selection path.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that operationalizes the APOT framework of Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} in a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing context. By mapping the APOT agents---SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), SOLPA (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), and SOLTA (Stage of Learning Transition Agent)---to three specialized CrewAI agents powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash, the system replaces deterministic scoring formulas and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning over answer correctness and response time. The LSAA (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is realized through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.

The dual-layer architecture---combining a synchronous rule-based fallback for real-time responsiveness with an asynchronous multi-agent AI pipeline for rich post-assessment insights---demonstrates that production-grade adaptive testing can coexist with computationally intensive LLM pipelines. The LLM-driven dynamic question generation eliminates the traditional requirement for pre-curated, statistically validated item banks.

The design-level analysis confirms that the three-agent APOT pipeline provides complete coverage of the adaptive transition space, logically consistent behavior across representative performance scenarios, and a natural language audit trail for every difficulty decision. The system demonstrates that LLM-native multi-agent architectures can implement adaptive testing logic that is simultaneously interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through simple prompt modification.

Future work will focus on: (1)~conducting user studies with diverse student populations to empirically validate the accuracy of LLM-predicted difficulty labels against expert annotations; (2)~extending the LSAA function with an explicit learning-style profiling agent that adapts question format based on detected learner preferences; (3)~integrating session-level memory (\texttt{memory=True} in CrewAI) to enable cross-question performance tracking and long-horizon difficulty planning by SOLTA; (4)~exploring prompt optimization techniques to reduce LLM output variability and improve structured output reliability; (5)~comparing LLM-based adaptation decisions against IRT-based ground truth on standardized item banks to quantify agreement rates; and (6)~deploying for concurrent multi-user assessment sessions with real-time difficulty dashboards for instructors, leveraging the Celery and Redis infrastructure already present in the technology stack.

